VALUES
(41, 6, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'to pray.', 60, 68, 'theology', 'Importance of Prayer', 'This passage suggests that prayer is essential for spiritual strength and guidance. Many scholars believe that Jesus'' practice of prayer before significant events underscores the necessity of seeking divine direction in our own lives. It teaches believers that prayer is not just a ritual but a vital connection to God that sustains us.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of Jesus'' prayer life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'he departed into a mountain to pray.', 32, 68, 'connection', 'Prayer and Solitude', 'This action of Jesus mirrors similar instances in the Gospels where He seeks solitude for prayer, such as in Luke 5:16, where it states, ''But Jesus often withdrew to lonely places and prayed.'' This connection emphasizes the importance of prayer and solitude in Jesus'' ministry and serves as a model for believers, highlighting the need to recharge spiritually away from the crowds.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 5:16", "description": "Jesus often withdrew for prayer."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'he departed into a mountain to pray.', 32, 68, 'theology', 'The Significance of Prayer', 'This passage suggests that prayer is vital for spiritual strength and guidance. Many scholars believe that Jesus'' retreat to pray signifies His dependence on the Father, reinforcing the doctrine of the Trinity and the relational aspect of prayer in the believer''s life. It invites reflection on the necessity of prayer in nurturing one''s relationship with God.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'he departed into a mountain to pray.', 32, 68, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''Pray''', 'προσεύχομαι (proseúchomai, G4336) - to pray, to make a request, to worship. This term emphasizes the act of turning one''s heart and mind towards God, signifying a deep engagement in communication with the divine. It underscores the relational aspect of prayer as not merely a ritual but a heartfelt dialogue with God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4336", "description": "Pray, to worship or make requests."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 46, 46, 'kjv', 'he departed into a mountain to pray.', 32, 68, 'question', 'Personal Reflection on Prayer', 'What does it mean for you to seek solitude for prayer as Jesus did? How can incorporating moments of quiet and prayer into your life transform your relationship with God and help you navigate challenges?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'And when even was come', 0, 22, 'greek', 'Understanding ''even''', 'ὀψίας (opsias, G3798) - evening, dusk. This term indicates the transition from day to night, symbolizing times of uncertainty and anticipation. In the biblical narrative, evening often represents moments of waiting or trials, setting the stage for divine intervention, as seen in this passage.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3798", "description": "Strong''s number for ''evening.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'the ship was in the midst of the sea', 24, 60, 'question', 'Reflections on Turmoil', 'What does it mean to be ''in the midst of the sea'' during turbulent times in our lives? How can we recognize Jesus'' presence in our struggles, much like the disciples did when they saw Him walking on the water? Reflect on the significance of faith in the face of adversity.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'the ship was in the midst of the sea', 24, 60, 'connection', 'Cross-reference to Psalm', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 107:23-24, where sailors find themselves in perilous conditions on the sea, calling out to the Lord. Both passages highlight God''s awareness and intervention in human struggles, emphasizing His providence in times of trouble. The disciples'' experience on the sea mirrors the psalmist''s description of divine rescue, illustrating God''s constant presence amidst chaos.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 107:23-24", "description": "Sailors in distress and God''s intervention"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'he alone on the land', 66, 86, 'theology', 'Christ''s Solitude and Prayer', 'This moment suggests the importance of solitude in Jesus'' ministry. Many scholars believe this highlights the necessity of prayer and communion with the Father, especially before significant acts of ministry. The contrast between Jesus'' solitude and the disciples'' struggle signifies the divine support available to believers during trials, reinforcing the idea that prayer prepares us for our challenges.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'the ship was in the midst of the sea', 24, 60, 'question', 'Understanding the Struggle', 'What does it mean for the disciples to be ''in the midst of the sea'' while Jesus is on land? How does this reflect our own experiences of feeling alone in trials while Jesus intercedes for us? This raises questions about faith, trust, and the nature of Christ''s presence in our challenges.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 47, 47, 'kjv', 'when even was come', 4, 22, 'greek', 'Evening Significance', 'ἐσπέρας (esperas, G2070) - evening. The mention of ''evening'' carries both literal and metaphorical significance, as it often represents times of transition or challenge in Scripture. This word invites reflection on how evening, a time of darkness, can symbolize our own struggles before the dawn of God''s deliverance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2070", "description": "Strong''s number for ''evening''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'toiling in rowing; for the wind was contrary unto them:', 16, 71, 'connection', 'Struggles in Adversity', 'This phrase echoes the struggles faced by the Israelites in Exodus 14:21-22, where they also encountered contrary winds during their escape from Egypt. Just as God intervened for them, this connection suggests that Jesus sees our struggles and comes to aid us in moments of adversity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 14:21-22", "description": "Israelites crossing the Red Sea amidst strong winds"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'walking upon the sea,', 133, 154, 'greek', 'Walking on Water', 'περιπατῶν (peripatōn, G4043) - walking, to walk about. This term indicates not just movement but signifies authority over the natural elements, reinforcing Jesus'' divine nature and power over creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4043", "description": "Greek word for walking, indicating authority"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'would have passed by them.', 159, 185, 'theology', 'Divine Presence', 'Many scholars believe this moment illustrates God''s desire to reveal Himself to us. The phrase suggests that while God is present in our struggles, He often waits for us to recognize Him and invite Him into our circumstances, emphasizing the importance of faith in experiencing His presence.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 48, 48, 'kjv', 'walking upon the sea,', 133, 154, 'question', 'Nature of Jesus'' Power', 'What does Jesus'' ability to walk on water reveal about His authority over nature and our daily challenges? How can recognizing His power in our lives change the way we approach difficulties?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'supposed it had been a spirit', 49, 78, 'greek', 'Greek Term for Spirit', 'πνεῦμα (pneuma, G4151) - spirit, breath, or wind. This term can refer to various spiritual beings or the human spirit. The disciples'' assumption reflects their cultural context, where spirits were often associated with fear and the unknown, demonstrating their lack of understanding of Jesus'' true identity.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4151", "description": "Strong''s number for ''spirit''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'But when they saw him walking upon the sea', 0, 42, 'theology', 'Christ''s Divine Authority', 'This passage suggests that Jesus'' ability to walk on water signifies his authority over nature, reinforcing the doctrine of his divinity. Many scholars believe this event illustrates not only Jesus'' miraculous power but also his sovereignty, inviting believers to trust in his presence during tumultuous times.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explores the significance of Christ''s miracles."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'But when they saw him', 0, 21, 'question', 'Recognition of Christ', 'What does it reveal about our perception of Christ when we fail to recognize Him in our struggles? How can we cultivate a clearer vision of His presence in our lives, especially during times of fear or uncertainty?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'walking upon the sea', 22, 42, 'connection', 'Walking on Water', 'This event echoes the Old Testament themes of God''s sovereignty over creation, particularly seen in Job 9:8 where it states, ''He alone stretches out the heavens and treads on the waves of the sea.'' This connection underscores Jesus'' divine authority and His identity as the Son of God, revealing His power over the natural world.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Job 9:8", "description": "Illustrates God''s control over the sea, paralleling Jesus'' actions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'they supposed it had been a spirit', 44, 78, 'theology', 'Understanding Spiritual Manifestations', 'This passage suggests the disciples'' initial fear and misunderstanding reflects a common theme in Scripture, where divine appearances are often met with fear. Many scholars believe this highlights the human tendency to misinterpret the divine, pointing to the need for faith to recognize God''s presence amidst life''s storms.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'cried out:', 84, 94, 'question', 'Crying Out in Fear', 'What does the disciples'' cry reveal about our own responses to fear in the face of the unknown? How can we learn to recognize Christ''s presence in our turbulent moments rather than succumbing to panic?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 49, 49, 'kjv', 'supposed it had been a spirit', 49, 78, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Spirit''', 'πνεῦμα (pneuma, G4151) - spirit, breath, wind. This term is significant as it can denote both the Holy Spirit and malevolent spiritual beings. The disciples'' assumption reflects their cultural understanding of spirits in the sea, highlighting their fear and the need for revelation to recognize Jesus.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4151", "description": "Strong''s number for ''spirit'' indicating its dual meanings."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'Be of good cheer: it is I; be not afraid.', 99, 140, 'connection', 'Encouragement in Fear', 'This phrase resonates with other instances of divine reassurance. For example, in Isaiah 41:10, God commands His people not to fear because He is with them. Similarly, in John 16:33, Jesus encourages His disciples to take heart because He has overcome the world. These connections illustrate a biblical theme of God''s presence and comfort in times of fear and uncertainty.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 41:10", "description": "God reassures His people not to fear."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 16:33", "description": "Jesus encourages His disciples amidst tribulations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'For they all saw him, and were troubled.', 0, 40, 'theology', 'Human Response to the Divine', 'This passage illustrates a common human reaction to the divine: fear and confusion. Many scholars believe this reflects the awe-inspiring nature of encountering the miraculous. The disciples'' immediate fear showcases their struggle to comprehend Jesus'' true identity and power, aligning with the biblical notion that God''s presence often elicits both reverence and apprehension.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'Be of good cheer: it is I; be not afraid.', 99, 140, 'question', 'Understanding Jesus'' Assurance', 'What does it mean for us today that Jesus tells His followers to ''be of good cheer''? How can we apply His assurance in our own moments of fear or uncertainty? Reflecting on this can deepen our faith and understanding of Christ''s continual presence in our lives.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'For they all saw him, and were troubled.', 0, 40, 'greek', 'Greek Term for ''Troubled''', 'ταράσσω (tarassō, G5015) - to stir up, trouble, or agitate. This term indicates a deep emotional disturbance, reflecting the disciples'' inner turmoil upon seeing Jesus. Their reaction highlights the overwhelming nature of the miraculous and the challenges of faith in the face of the unknown.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5015", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'Be of good cheer: it is I; be not afraid.', 99, 140, 'theology', 'Comfort in Christ''s Presence', 'This phrase emphasizes the comforting nature of Jesus'' presence amid fear. Many scholars believe that His assurance, ''Be of good cheer,'' reflects His divine authority and ability to calm our fears. It suggests that in times of distress or uncertainty, the believer can find peace through faith in Christ, who walks with us through our storms.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the comfort found in Christ''s words during trials."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'For they all saw him, and were troubled.', 0, 40, 'connection', 'Fear and Recognition', 'This moment parallels Matthew 14:26, where the disciples also react with fear upon seeing Jesus walking on water. The connection highlights a common human response to the supernatural—initial fear followed by recognition of Christ''s true nature. It reminds readers that encountering the divine can provoke fear, yet it is often in that fear where faith begins to grow.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 14:26", "description": "Similar reaction of fear from the disciples upon seeing Jesus."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'be not afraid.', 126, 140, 'greek', 'Greek Term for Fear', 'φόβος (phobos, G5401) - fear, terror. This term underlines the deep-rooted instinct of fear that grips the disciples. The usage of ''phobos'' in this context indicates not just a momentary fright but a profound existential anxiety, which Jesus addresses directly to instill courage and faith.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5401", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word for fear."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 50, 50, 'kjv', 'immediately he talked with them, and saith unto them, Be of good cheer:', 45, 116, 'question', 'Christ''s Immediate Response', 'What does it reveal about Jesus'' character that He immediately reassures His fearful disciples? This prompts reflection on how we might respond to our own fears—do we seek reassurance from Christ, and how do we recognize His presence in our lives during troubling times?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 51, 51, 'kjv', 'the wind ceased', 44, 59, 'theology', 'Divine Authority Over Nature', 'This phrase illustrates the theological concept of Jesus'' divine authority. Many scholars believe that his ability to calm the wind signifies his role as the Messiah, fulfilling Old Testament expectations of God controlling the forces of nature (see Psalm 107:29). This reinforces the belief that Jesus embodies God''s power and presence among his people.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Psalm 107:29", "description": "God''s control over the storm."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 51, 51, 'kjv', 'sore amazed in themselves beyond measure', 75, 115, 'question', 'Understanding Our Amazement', 'What does it mean to be ''sore amazed'' at Jesus'' actions? How does our response to his miracles reflect our understanding of his nature? Consider how often we recognize his power in our own lives, and whether we allow ourselves to be amazed by his presence and works.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 51, 51, 'kjv', 'And he went up unto them into the ship;', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Walking on Water', 'This event parallels another instance of Jesus calming a storm in Mark 4:39, where He demonstrates authority over nature. The connection highlights His divine power and reassures believers of His ability to intervene in their lives during turbulent times.', 'arrow.triangle.branch', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Mark 4:39", "description": "Jesus calms the storm, showcasing His divine authority."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 51, 51, 'kjv', 'and the wind ceased:', 40, 60, 'greek', 'Ceased (Kōlūō)', 'κόλυν (kōlūō, G2868) - to cease, to stop. This term emphasizes the immediate obedience of nature to Jesus'' presence, illustrating His authority and the peace that comes from His intervention.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2868", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word meaning ''to cease''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 51, 51, 'kjv', 'and they were sore amazed in themselves beyond measure, and wondered.', 61, 130, 'theology', 'Nature of Wonder', 'This passage suggests that the disciples'' amazement reflects a deeper theological truth about the nature of faith and recognition of Jesus'' divinity. It serves as a reminder that encountering Jesus often leads to awe and reverence, challenging believers to grow in understanding of His nature.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 51, 51, 'kjv', 'and they were sore amazed in themselves beyond measure, and wondered.', 61, 130, 'question', 'Reflections on Amazement', 'What does it mean for us to be ''sore amazed'' at the works of Christ? How can we cultivate a sense of wonder in our own faith journey as we witness His actions in our lives today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 52, 52, 'kjv', 'For they considered not the miracle of the loaves: for their heart was hardened.', 0, 80, 'connection', 'Connection to Exodus', 'This verse recalls the Israelites'' hardened hearts in Exodus 14:12, where they doubted God''s provision despite witnessing miracles. This comparison highlights a recurring theme of disbelief in the face of divine intervention, emphasizing the need for faith in God''s capabilities.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 14:12", "description": "Israelites doubting God''s provision despite miracles."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 52, 52, 'kjv', 'considered not the miracle of the loaves', 9, 49, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Considered''', 'ἔγνωσαν (egnōsan, G1097) - to know, recognize, understand. The use of this term indicates a deeper failure to grasp the significance of Jesus'' miracle. It suggests that their lack of recognition stems from a spiritual blindness, which resonates with the theme of understanding divine truths throughout Mark''s Gospel.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1097", "description": "Greek term for ''considered'' or ''know.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 52, 52, 'kjv', 'for their heart was hardened', 51, 79, 'theology', 'The Hardening of Hearts', 'This passage suggests a theological concept of spiritual hardening, akin to Romans 11:25, where Paul discusses Israel''s partial hardening. Many scholars believe this reflects a divine judgment that limits understanding and responsiveness to God''s actions, reinforcing the need for a soft heart toward God''s revelations.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 11:25", "description": "Paul discusses the hardening of Israel''s heart."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 52, 52, 'kjv', 'their heart was hardened', 55, 79, 'question', 'Reflecting on Hardness of Heart', 'What causes our hearts to harden against the truths of God? This verse challenges us to examine our own responsiveness to His miracles and teachings, prompting reflection on how we might be overlooking His presence and work in our lives.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 53, 53, 'kjv', 'drew to the shore', 74, 91, 'theology', 'Divine Guidance', 'This phrase suggests the sovereignty of Christ in guiding His disciples to safety. Many scholars believe that the act of drawing to the shore symbolizes the transition from turmoil to peace, reflecting God''s presence and guidance in our lives, especially in times of distress.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 53, 53, 'kjv', 'passed over', 18, 29, 'greek', 'Greek Insight', 'παράγω (paragō, G3928) - to pass by, to go past. This term emphasizes the movement from one state to another, not just physically but also spiritually, as the disciples transition from fear to faith.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3928", "description": "Strong''s number for deeper study into the term."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 53, 53, 'kjv', 'the land of Gennesaret', 46, 68, 'connection', 'Geographical Significance', 'Gennesaret is mentioned in parallel accounts in Matthew 14:34-36 and Luke 9:10-17, indicating its importance as a region of Jesus'' ministry. This connection matters because it highlights the consistent geographical context of Jesus'' miracles and teachings, showing how His presence transformed various communities.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 14:34-36", "description": "Another account of Jesus healing in Gennesaret."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Luke 9:10-17", "description": "Jesus'' ministry in the same region."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 53, 53, 'kjv', 'drew to the shore', 74, 91, 'greek', 'Greek Term Insight', 'ἀφικνέομαι (aphikneomai, G5342) - to arrive, to come to. This term emphasizes the intentionality of Jesus and His disciples in reaching their destination, reflecting a sense of purpose in their ministry as they arrived to serve those in need.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5342", "description": "Greek term denoting arrival and purpose."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 53, 53, 'kjv', 'when they had passed over', 4, 29, 'theology', 'Journey and Transition', 'This phrase suggests a transition from one state to another, which many scholars believe reflects the spiritual journey of the disciples. They are moving from doubt and confusion, as seen earlier in the passage, to a place of recognition and action in Gennesaret. It illustrates the theme of faith development in the believer''s life.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Mark 6:51-52", "description": "Contextual understanding of the disciples'' journey."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 53, 53, 'kjv', 'land of Gennesaret', 50, 68, 'question', 'Reflecting on Place', 'What does it mean for Jesus to come to a specific place like Gennesaret, and how does this inform your understanding of His willingness to meet people in their context? How does this challenge you to recognize the significance of your own surroundings in God''s plan?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 54, 54, 'kjv', 'straightway they knew him,', 41, 67, 'connection', 'Recognition of Christ', 'This immediate recognition of Jesus by the disciples parallels instances in John 1:29, where John the Baptist identifies Jesus as the ''Lamb of God.'' Both passages emphasize the clarity with which Jesus'' identity is understood, highlighting His divine nature and mission. Such recognition suggests that familiarity with Christ leads to deeper understanding of His purpose and authority.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 1:29", "description": "John the Baptist identifies Jesus as the Lamb of God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 54, 54, 'kjv', 'And when they were come out of the ship, straightway they knew him,', 0, 67, 'theology', 'Christ''s Manifestation', 'This passage illustrates the theological concept of Christ''s omnipresence and recognition. Many scholars believe that the immediate recognition signifies not just familiarity but an unveiling of His divine nature. The disciples'' ability to recognize Him immediately speaks to how God''s presence can be known and felt in significant moments, reinforcing the belief that Christ is always near to those who seek Him.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 54, 54, 'kjv', 'they knew him,', 53, 67, 'greek', 'Knowledge of Christ', 'γινώσκω (ginōskō, G1097) - to know, understand, perceive. This term conveys a deeper relational knowledge rather than mere recognition. It implies an intimate understanding of Jesus'' character and mission, emphasizing that true knowledge of Christ comes from experience and relationship, not just observation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1097", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 6, 54, 54, 'kjv', 'And when they were come out of the ship,', 0, 40, 'question', 'Response to Christ''s Presence', 'What does it mean for us today to recognize Christ in our everyday lives, as the disciples did upon exiting the ship? How might our immediate responses to His presence shape our faith journey and interactions with others?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');